
USE CASE DRAFT: T1021 Remote Services



ATTACK DESCRIPTION
Adversaries may use remote services to gain access to systems, execute commands, move laterally across a network, or maintain persistent accesss. Common remote services include Remote Desktop Protocool, Windows Remote Management, Secure Shell, and SMB administrative shares.

ATT&CK Mapping
Technique: T1021 - Remote Services

Tactics:
- Lateral Movement
- Persistence
- Initial Access
 

Detection Objective
Identify successful remote logons and remote service activity that may indicate unauthorized access or lateral movement between systems

Potential Data Sources
- Windows Security Logs
- Event ID 4624(Successful Logon)
- Event ID 4625(Failed Logon)
- Sysmon Event Logs
- Remote Desktop Service Logs
- Windows Event Viewer

Detection Idea
Monitor for successful remote logons, particularly Logon Type 10(Remote Interactive/RDP), unusual source systems, or repeated remote access attempts from the same account.

Examples of suspicious behavior:
- Succesful RDP logon from another system
- Multiple failed remote logon attempts followed by a successful logon
- Remote logons occuring outside normal business hours
- Administrative accounts using remote services unexpectedly
- A user accessing multiple systems through RDP within a short timeframe
- Remote access from unusual IP addresses



Alert Concept: Potential Unauthorized Remote Access Detected
Description: Generate an alert when a succesful remote logon(Logon Type 10) is detected from an unusual account, system, or time period

Trigger Condition: Succesful Windows Event Logon(Event ID 4624) with Logon Type 10 detected
Severity: Medium


